    "3 As it often happens, however, it did not take long before ideas and intuitions from science fiction became part of AI's agenda.",
    "In 1997, Rosalind Picard published her seminal Affective Computing, providing a manifesto for research on AI systems that could recognize, express and possibly have-more on this in a momentemotions and affects.",
    "Nowadays, affective computing is for all intents and purposes a branch of artificial intelligence (see Calvo et al. 2015), and together with other disciplinessuch as social robotics-works to improve artificial systems' emotion-laden interactions with humans.",
    "But how, exactly, can artificial systems interact with us in an emotionally meaningful way?",
    "Picard argued that \"if we want computers to be genuinely intelligent, to adapt to us, and to interact naturally with us, then they will need the ability to recognize and express emotions, to have emotions\" (Picard 1997)."
